",["$r","p",null,{"children":["If you look at ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"ProductTable"}]," (lavender), you’ll see that the table header (containing the “Name” and “Price” labels) isn’t its own component. This is a matter of preference, and you could go either way. For this example, it is a part of ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"ProductTable"}]," because it appears inside the ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"ProductTable"}],"’s list. However, if this header grows to be complex (e.g., if you add sorting), you can move it into its own ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"ProductTableHeader"}]," component."]}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":"Now that you’ve identified the components in the mockup, arrange them into a hierarchy. Components that appear within another component in the mockup should appear as a child in the hierarchy:"}],"
