",["$r","DeepDive",null,{"children":[["$r","h4",null,{"id":"props-vs-state","children":"Props vs State "}],["$r","p",null,{"children":"There are two types of “model” data in React: props and state. The two are very different:"}],["$r","ul",null,{"children":["
",["$r","li",null,{"children":[["$r","a",null,{"href":"/learn/passing-props-to-a-component","children":[["$r","strong",null,{"children":"Props"}]," are like arguments you pass"]}]," to a function. They let a parent component pass data to a child component and customize its appearance. For example, a ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"Form"}]," can pass a ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"color"}]," prop to a ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"Button"}],"."]}],"
",["$r","li",null,{"children":[["$r","a",null,{"href":"/learn/state-a-components-memory","children":[["$r","strong",null,{"children":"State"}]," is like a component’s memory."]}]," It lets a component keep track of some information and change it in response to interactions. For example, a ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"Button"}]," might keep track of ",["$r","code",null,{"children":"isHovered"}]," state."]}],"
"]}],["$r","p",null,{"children":["Props and state are different, but they work together. A parent component will often keep some information in state (so that it can change it), and ",["$r","em",null,{"children":"pass it down"}]," to child components as their props. It’s okay if the difference still feels fuzzy on the first read. It takes a bit of practice for it to really stick!"]}]]}],"
",["$r","h2",null,{"id":"step-4-identify-where-your-state-should-live","children":"Step 4: Identify where your state should live "}],"
",["$r","p",null,{"children":["After identifying your app’s minimal state data, you need to identify which component is responsible for changing this state, or ",["$r","em",null,{"children":"owns"}]," the state. Remember: React uses one-way data flow, passing data down the component hierarchy from parent to child component. It may not be immediately clear which component should own what state. This can be challenging if you’re new to this concept, but you can figure it out by following these steps!"]}],"
